time_trend_data.indicator_description: Workers’ compensation is a type of insurance that provides medical care for workers who are injured or become ill as a direct result of their job. Hospitalizations billed to workers' compensation represent only a portion of work-related injuries that require hospital care. It is important to realize that workers’ compensation policies vary from state-to-state with respect to the types of workers covered and the types of injuries and illnesses eligible for compensation.

Compare.graph_title: Trends in  Hospitalizations Billed to Workers’ Compensation - 3-Year Average Annual Rate 2001-2003 to 2016-2018

info.info_how_calculated: Number of hospitalizations among employed NYC residents aged 16 years or older with workers’ compensation listed as the primary payer over a 3-year period, divided by the population of employed NYC residents aged 16 years or older in each of these years, expressed as a 3-year average annual rate per 100,000.
info.info_source: Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System, U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Current Population Survey
